Good catch — this is exactly the right place to lock that down. Below are clean additions you can drop straight into the existing Phase 3 README. No reflow needed.

Phase 3 Authority Statement

Phase 3 is the only phase where money and execution are defined.

Phase 0 defines permission to exist

Phase 1 defines permission to test

Phase 2 defines theory-only reasoning

Phase 3 defines execution authority and licensing terms

No other phase authorizes execution, commercialization, or deployment—explicitly or implicitly.

Execution and Commercialization Definition

For licensing purposes, commercialization is defined by outcome, not intent.

What Counts as Commercialization (License Required)

Any of the following actions require a paid execution license:

Building, prototyping, or fabricating hardware based on this work

Testing (lab, field, analog, or environmental) beyond Phase 1 scope

Simulation performed for implementation or validation

Use in proposals, bids, grants, or contracts (government or commercial)

Integration into a larger system or architecture

Deployment, demonstration, or operational use

Manufacturing, even at pilot or low-volume scale

Internal use that supports revenue-generating activity

Derivative designs intended for execution

If the work touches the real world, supports funding, or influences procurement, it is execution.

What Does NOT Count as Commercialization (No License Required)

The following uses are explicitly allowed without an execution license:

Reading and internal review

Conceptual reasoning and critique

Academic discussion or informal analysis

High-level reference without implementation

Education or training not tied to execution

Independent re-derivation without reuse of this material

Private evaluation that does not result in build, test, or proposal activity

Thinking is free.
Doing is not.

Enforcement Rule

Intent is irrelevant; outcome controls

Execution without a license automatically terminates permission to use Phase 3 materials

Phase 0 or Phase 1 access does not waive Phase 3 requirements

