Phase 3 Authority

Phase 3 is the sole phase that defines execution and payment.

Phase 0 grants permission to exist

Phase 1 grants permission to test within defined limits

Phase 2 is theory-only and expressly non-executable

Phase 3 defines execution rights, commercialization, and license fees

No execution rights exist outside Phase 3.

Definition of Execution and Commercialization

For licensing purposes, execution and commercialization are defined by outcome, not intent.

Actions Requiring an Execution License

An execution license is required prior to any of the following:

Building, fabricating, or prototyping hardware

Testing beyond Phase 1 scope (lab, field, environmental, or analog)

Simulation performed for validation or implementation

Use in proposals, bids, grants, or contracts

Integration into any system, architecture, or program

Demonstration, deployment, or operational use

Manufacturing at any scale

Internal use supporting revenue, procurement, or funding

Creation of derivative works intended for execution

Any application of these materials to real-world activity constitutes execution.

Actions Not Requiring an Execution License

The following activities do not constitute execution:

Reading or reviewing materials

Internal discussion or critique

Academic or educational analysis

High-level reference without implementation

Independent re-derivation without reuse of this material

These activities do not authorize execution.

Enforcement

Intent is irrelevant; outcome controls

Execution without a license terminates all rights automatically

Phase 0 or Phase 1 access does not waive Phase 3 requirements

